# Java conventions

Imports and formatting: [stomp4j-format-imports.mdc](stomp4j-format-imports.mdc) (required on every Java edit).

## Style

- **Dead code:** remove unused locals, parameters, fields, and private methods in every change you touch.
- String building: [stomp4j-strings.mdc](stomp4j-strings.mdc).
- **Type names:** PascalCase — `^[A-Z][a-zA-Z0-9]*$`. Version classes: `Stomp1_0`, `Stomp1_1`, `Stomp1_2`.

## `var` and local variables

- Prefer **`var`** when the type is clear from the RHS.
- **Inline** throwaway locals when each value is used once and the chain stays readable (~120 chars).
- Keep a local when reused or when splitting aids debugging.

## Functional style

- Prefer streams, `Optional`, `map` / `filter` / `flatMap` for straight pipelines.
- Use `ifPresentOrElse`, `orElseThrow`, `orElseGet` instead of `isPresent()` + `get()`.
- Imperative code is fine for NIO loops, transport I/O, and multi-step mutations.

## Comments

- Explain **non-obvious** behaviour only — see [stomp4j-in-code-documentation.mdc](stomp4j-in-code-documentation.mdc).
- Class-level **Responsibility Design** blocks — see [stomp4j-class-responsibilities.mdc](stomp4j-class-responsibilities.mdc).
- STOMP spec rationale, architecture decisions, and rejected alternatives belong in comments at the decision point.

## Logging

- Always **SLF4J** — never `System.out`, `System.err`, or `java.util.logging`.
- One static logger per class: `LoggerFactory.getLogger(MyClass.class)`.
- Use **`{}` placeholders** — never string concatenation in log messages ([FAQ: fastest way of logging](https://www.slf4j.org/faq.html#logging_performance)).
- Do not log secrets, passwords, or full credentials.
- Core modules depend on **`slf4j-api` only**; never declare a logging provider/binding in library code ([manual: libraries](https://www.slf4j.org/manual.html#libraries)).

### Parameterized messages (traditional API)

The typical pattern passes **values already in scope** as arguments. SLF4J checks the level first; only then does it format the message and call `toString()` on those arguments.

```java
logger.debug("Temperature set to {}. Old value was {}.", newT, oldT);
```

This avoids the cost of string concatenation when the level is disabled. It does **not** defer Java expression evaluation — any method call in the argument list runs before the logger method is invoked.

### Fluent API and lazy `Supplier` arguments (SLF4J 2.0+)

Use `atTrace()` / `atDebug()` / `atInfo()` / `atWarn()` / `atError()` when building the event needs deferred work ([manual: fluent logging API](https://www.slf4j.org/manual.html#fluent)). For a disabled level, the returned `LoggingEventBuilder` is a no-op.

- **Terminate every chain with `.log()`** — omitting it logs nothing.
- Pass **expensive expressions** via `addArgument(Supplier)`, not as direct method-call arguments.

| Argument | Pattern |
|---|---|
| Literal, local, or value already computed | `logger.debug("interval: {}", interval)` or `logger.atDebug().log("interval: {}", interval)` |
| Method call, chained access, `encode()`, `formatted()`, or other non-trivial work | `logger.atDebug().addArgument(() -> expensive()).log("…: {}")` |

```java
// ❌ headers().get() runs even when INFO is disabled
logger.info("Heart beat interval: {}", connected.headers().get(Header.HEART_BEAT));

// ✅ Supplier evaluated only when INFO is enabled (manual example pattern)
logger.atInfo()
      .setMessage("Heart beat interval: {}")
      .addArgument(() -> connected.headers().get(Header.HEART_BEAT))
      .log();
```

Prefer `addKeyValue("name", value)` over embedding structured fields in the message when key-value context helps operators ([manual: fluent API](https://www.slf4j.org/manual.html#fluent)).

Do not wrap parameterized calls in `isDebugEnabled()` / `isInfoEnabled()` guards — that double-checks the level; use `{}` or the fluent API instead.

Existing lazy-argument examples: `AbstractNioTcpTransport`, `WebSocketTransport`, `ClientHeartbeat`.

Exceptions and error paths: [stomp4j-exceptions.mdc](stomp4j-exceptions.mdc) — domain types, no broad `catch (Exception)`, ERROR logging on failures.

## JPMS

- Public API types must be in `exports` packages.
- Internal implementation stays in non-exported packages (`internal`, `channels`, `session`).
- When adding SPI, update both `module-info.java` and `META-INF/services`.

